"Each and every day, vast amounts of data are being created and collected by companies around the globe. In many cases, users are being asked to sign up for ever more invasive user agreements allowing companies to gather more and more private data – and they often don't know how their data will be shared. So what are the consequences for marketers, users and policy makers? And what are we likely to see in terms of regulation in the future? Every day, vast amounts of data are being created and collected by companies around the globe. Users are being asked to provide ever more private data – and they often don't know how their data will be shared. Hariprasad Pichai, Dr Sai Prakash Iyer, Thomas Kuruvilla of management consultancy Arthur D Little take a closer look at the consequences this has for marketers, users and policy makers. They also examine how users could make more informed choices about the information they share, and future directions for regulation."
